---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "../components/PageHeader.astro";
const title = "About me";
---

<BaseLayout pageTitle={title}>
  <div class="grid">
    <PageHeader heading={title}>Get to know me a bit better</PageHeader>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        I’ve always been fascinated by the intersection of psychology,
        technology, and design. This curiosity led me to study psychology. First
        neuropsychology, because I was captivated by how the brain works, and
        later applied cognitive psychology, where I learned how scientific
        insights about human thought and behaviour can be applied in practical
        settings.
      </p>
      <p>
        During that second master’s, a course on human-computer interaction
        opened my eyes to UX as a career. I realised it was possible to combine
        psychology, tech, and design into a single profession and I was hooked.
        An internship at a UX research consultancy gave me a hands-on
        introduction to usability testing and user research, but I quickly
        discovered I wanted to do more than evaluate interfaces. I wanted to
        design them.
      </p>
      <p>
        This led me to a post-master in user-system interaction, where I learned
        the principles of user-centred design and earned a professional
        doctorate in engineering. My first role as a UX designer marked the
        start of my career, and over the years the technology side has grown
        increasingly central. Learning front-end development allowed me to
        bridge the gap between design and code, and today I consider myself a
        design engineer.
      </p>
      <p>
        I thrive at the intersection of design and engineering, translating
        research and user needs into accessible, scalable, and maintainable
        interfaces. Whether building design systems, implementing components, or
        collaborating across teams, my focus is always on creating products that
        are not only visually and interactively strong but also usable and
        inclusive.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
